{{Use Australian English|date=November 2018}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}
'''Dr. Arnold "Puggy" Hunter''' was a pioneer in [[Aboriginal Australians#Health|Australian Aboriginal health]] and recipient of the 2001 [[Human Rights Medal (Australia)|Australian Human Rights Medal]].

Puggy was the elected [[Chairman|chairperson]] of the [[National Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Organisation]], (NACCHO), which is the peak national advisory body on Aboriginal health. NACCHO has a membership of over 100 Aboriginal Community Controlled Health Services and is the representative body of these services. Puggy was the inaugural Chair of NACCHO from 1991 until his death.<ref name="NACCHO">{{cite news|title=A Special Tribute Edition |url=http://www.naccho.org.au/download/naccho-historical/NACCHO%20Tribute%20edition.pdf |publisher=NACCHO news |date=September 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311040144/http://www.naccho.org.au/download/naccho-historical/NACCHO%20Tribute%20edition.pdf |archivedate=2015-03-11 }}</ref>

Puggy was the vice-chairperson of the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Council, the Federal Health Minister’s main advisory body on Aboriginal health established in 1996. He was also Chair of the National Public Health Partnership Aboriginal and Islander Health Working Group which reports to the Partnership and to the Australian Health Ministers Advisory Council. He was a member of the [[Australian Pharmaceutical Advisory Council]] (APAC), the General Practice Partnership Advisory Council, the Joint Advisory Group on Population Health and the National Health Priority Areas Action Council as well as a number of other key Aboriginal health policy and advisory groups on national issues.<ref name="NACCHO"/>

Puggy had a long and passionate role in the struggle for justice for Aboriginal people. He was born in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] in 1951, where his parents had fled [[Broome, Western Australia|Broome]] and [[Aboriginal history of Western Australia|Western Australian native welfare policies]].<ref name="NACCHO"/>

Numerous Australian [[Scholarship|scholarships]] are named in his honour.

He was quoted in [[Parliament of Australia|Australian Parliament]] as saying: "You white people have the hearing problems because you do not seem to hear us." <ref name="parliament">{{cite news |title=Hansard |url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber%2Fhansardr%2F2001-09-24%2F0195;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F2001-09-24%2F0000%22 |publisher=Parliament of Australia |date=24 September 2011}}</ref>

