{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}
'''Sandra Lorraine Coney''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSO}} (born 22 October 1944) is a New Zealand local body politician, writer, [[feminist]], [[historian]], and women's health campaigner.

==Activist career==
She is best known for her co-authorship (with [[Phillida Bunkle]]) of a ''[[Metro (magazine)|Metro]]'' magazine article that alleged that women had been experimented on, without their consent, at [[National Women's Hospital]] in [[Auckland]]. The article, titled 'The Unfortunate Experiment', led to the controversial [[Cartwright Inquiry]], which confirmed the article's allegations. The article and the subsequent inquiry are seen as a turning point in healthcare ethics in New Zealand.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}

Coney has been involved in other women's health causes, and in 1984 co-founded with Bunkle [[Women's Health Action]] to co-ordinate claims by women who had been injured by the [[Dalkon Shield]] [[IUD]].<ref>[http://www.everybody.co.nz/page-9b60454c-4546-432a-8003-827ca58ec4b2.aspx Women's Health Action – Everybody – Health Information for New Zealanders<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070408055716/http://www.everybody.co.nz/page-9b60454c-4546-432a-8003-827ca58ec4b2.aspx |date=8 April 2007 }}</ref>
Coney was the co-founder of the feminist magazine ''[[Broadsheet (magazine)|Broadsheet]]'', which she co-edited for 14 years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Jeremy |title=Influential Kiwis talk about their Influences |url= http://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/ideas/20091206 |accessdate=7 May 2014 |newspaper=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=6 December 2009}}</ref> She is the author or editor of 14 books, including the major Suffrage Centennial publication ''Standing in the Sunshine'' (1993), which was also a television series. She wrote a regular column of political and social comment for the Sunday-Times for 16 years from 1986.

She is also involved in the local politics of the [[Piha]] area such as the unsuccessful campaign against the Piha cafe. She has also written an history of Piha, and is currently researching [[Anzac]] soldiers from the Piha area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arc.govt.nz/arc/about-arc/meet-the-councillors/sandra-coney.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 April 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070202165318/http://arc.govt.nz/arc/about-arc/meet-the-councillors/sandra-coney.cfm |archivedate=2 February 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/search/story.cfm?storyid=0000D672-5BE3-1628-96FF83027AF1010E | work=The New Zealand Herald | title=NZ Herald: New Zealand's Latest News, Business, Sport, Weather, Travel, Technology, Entertainment, Politics, Finance, Health, Environment and Science}}</ref>

Her father was Tom Pearce, who was ARC chair from 1965 to 1976 and a [[New Zealand Rugby Union|New Zealand Rugby Football Union]] administrator.

==Political career==
{{AC header}}
{{Auckland Council|affiliation=Best for the West|colour=lightgreen|ward=[[Waitakere]]|start=[[Auckland local elections, 2010|2010]]|end=2013}}
{{end}}Between 2001 and 2010, Coney represented [[Waitakere City]] on the [[Auckland Regional Council]] (ARC), and served as Chair of the Parks and Heritage Committee between 2004 and 2010.

In October 2010, she was elected as a representative of the [[Waitakere Ward]] on the [[Auckland Council]] on the Best for the West ticket. She was also elected as an independent representative on the [[District Health Board|Waitemata District Health Board]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=2010 Election Results|publisher=[[Auckland Transition Agency]]/[[Auckland Council]]|url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/2010Elections/Results/Pages/Home.aspx|date=October 2010|accessdate=17 October 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011092108/http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/2010ELECTIONS/RESULTS/Pages/Home.aspx|archivedate=11 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In the [[2013 Auckland local elections]], Coney stood down as a councillor, endorsing fellow Future West candidate [[Christine Rose (politician)|Christine Rose]] for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last=Orsman |first=Bernard |date=2 August 2013 |title=Heritage hero Coney exiting council to focus on West |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10906812 |newspaper=[[New Zealand Herald]] |location=Auckland |publisher=Wilson and Horton |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> She was re-elected to the Waitemata District Health Board,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Pages/Finalresults-DHB.aspx |title=Elections: Final results – District health board |author= |date=2013 |website=Auckland Council Website |publisher=[[Auckland Council]] |accessdate=7 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017024922/http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz:80/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Pages/Finalresults-DHB.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> and was elected to a new role as chair of the Waitākere Ranges Local Board,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/representativesbodies/LocalBoards/WaitakereRangeslocalboard/Pages/contact.aspx |title=Contact Waitākere Ranges Local Board |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |website=Auckland Council Website |publisher=Auckland Council |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> having received the most votes of any of the board's members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/lbfinalresults2013.pdf |title=Local boards final results |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |page=5 |format=PDF |date=17 October 2013 |website=Auckland Council Website |publisher=Auckland Council |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref>

At the [[Auckland local elections, 2016|2016 Auckland elections]], Coney stood for Future West and was re-elected to the Waitākere Ranges Local Board, the Waitemata District Health Board and the Portage Licensing Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/licensingtrusts2016.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019015948/http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/licensingtrusts2016.pdf |archivedate=19 October 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/aucklanddhb2016.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019014606/http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/aucklanddhb2016.pdf |archivedate=19 October 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/Confirmedlocalelectionresults2016.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019000339/http://www.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz/EN/AboutCouncil/HowCouncilWorks/Elections/Documents/Confirmedlocalelectionresults2016.pdf |archivedate=19 October 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>

==Writing career==
Coney is the author of more than 30 books on topics including history, feminism, and women's health care.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dickey |first=Delwyn |date=17 September 2013 |title=Radio astronomy's Pakiri role |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/rodney-times/9175185/Radio-astronomys-Pakiri-role |newspaper=[[Rodney Times]] |location=Orewa, New Zealand |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3A%22Sandra+Coney%22&fq=x0%3Abook |title=Search results for 'au:"Sandra Coney"' > 'Book' |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |website=[[WorldCat]] |publisher=[[OCLC]] |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref>

